er confidence interval widths.</p></sec></sec><sec id="Sec30"><title>Beliefs about increasing physical activity</title><p>All intervention groups reported a stronger intention to be more physically active than control participants (Table&#x000a0;<xref rid="Tab3" ref-type="table">3</xref>). The other constructs also generally showed an advantage over the control arm but had low internal consistency.<table-wrap id="Tab3"><label>Table 3</label><caption><p>Beliefs about increasing physical activity by arm and comparisons between each VBI and control</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th/><th>Motivational VBI Mean (SD)</th><th>Pedometer VBI Mean (SD)</th><th>Combined VBI Mean (SD)</th><th>Control Mean (SD)</th><th>Motivational VBI relative to Control - Difference in means (95&#x000a0;% CI) <sup>a</sup>
